In this step we concentrate on the first jet you want to annotate (if there are more than one).

In this step we concentrate on the first jet you want to annotate (if there are more than one).

Step 2: Mark the base of the jet in the time frame where the jet ends (or in the last time frame if it does not end in that movie).

Step 3: Box the jet in the time frame of your choice - you can rotate the box!

In this step we concentrate on the first jet you want to annotate (if there are more than one).

Step 3: Box the jet in the time frame of your choice - you can rotate the box!

The "base" of the jet refers to where a jet is touching the Sun - where on the Sun it is "launching" from. By marking the base in both the start and end frames

In this step we concentrate on the first jet you want to annotate (if there are more than one).

Step 1: Mark the base of the jet in the time frame where the jet begins (or in the first time frame if the jet has already started when the movie starts).

Step 2: Mark the base of the jet in the time frame where the jet ends (or in the last time frame if it does not end in that movie).

Step 3: Box the jet in the time frame of your choice - you can rotate the box!
